      "writtenOn": "2020-04-17T15:40:07Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "@jcgregorio may have more, but here\u0027s from my perspective:\nCompare using os/exec.Cmd.StdinPipe() (returns a WriteCloser) and doing the same thing with //go/go/exec.Command. In the former, I just start writing and then close it when done. For the latter, I have to set up my own bytes.Buffer (or something) and pass it in.\n\nSimilar extra steps are needed for dealing standard out and error.",
      "parentUuid": "ea0bf922_80fa6a2c",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 54,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 64
      },
      "revId": "1b1585ae4af7d0acb84a76312a4a4f0b9f23e16e",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6efb3ccd_a5100c0a",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 11,
      "author": {
        "id": 5205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-17T16:02:35Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, the inversion of the pipe directions is what made me move away from go/exec, for example look at:\n\n  https://github.com/google/skia-buildbot/blob/master/perf/go/git/git.go#L453\n\nNote that I can just pass the stdout, as an io.Reader, to parseGitRevLogStream which uses a bufio.Scanner.\n\nIn order to use go/exec I would have needed to spin up another Go routine and copy the io.Writer that go/exec returns to turn it into an io.Reader.",
      "parentUuid": "d68a93ad_a9e2638a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 54,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 64
      },
      "revId": "1b1585ae4af7d0acb84a76312a4a4f0b9f23e16e",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f3d977e2_28fa641a",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 11,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-17T16:20:22Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Ah, yeah, if you\u0027re doing anything interesting with streaming input and output, go/exec doesn\u0027t provide helpers for that.  What threw me was the use of \"inversion\", since both os/exec and go/exec use io.Reader for Stdin and io.Writer for Stdout/Stderr.  The difference is that os/exec provides the Std[out|err|in]Pipe helpers, which do exactly what you suggest, creating an io.Pipe and spinning up a goroutine to do the copy.\n\nI still think go/exec is more usable in the most common case, ie. run this command in this directory and give me the output, but that has more to do with the handy wrappers in that package than with the actual functionality.",
      "parentUuid": "6efb3ccd_a5100c0a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 9,
        "startChar": 54,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 64
      },
      "revId": "1b1585ae4af7d0acb84a76312a4a4f0b9f23e16e",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d19775e3_241b2389",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
